pr_body:
<!--         ----------------------------------------------------------------
                MAKE SURE YOUR PR GETS THE ATTENTION IT DESERVES!
                ----------------------------------------------------------------

*  FORMAT IT RIGHT:
      https://www.numpy.org/devdocs/dev/development_workflow.html#writing-the-commit-message

*  IF IT'S A NEW FEATURE OR API CHANGE, TEST THE WATERS:
      https://www.numpy.org/devdocs/dev/development_workflow.html#get-the-mailing-list-s-opinion

*  HIT ALL THE GUIDELINES:
      https://numpy.org/devdocs/dev/index.html#guidelines

*  WHAT TO DO IF WE HAVEN'T GOTTEN BACK TO YOU:
      https://www.numpy.org/devdocs/dev/development_workflow.html#getting-your-pr-reviewed
-->

This draft PR implements the F2PY frontend with `argparse` library. The aim is to split up one big [f2py2e.py](https://github.com/numpy/numpy/blob/main/numpy/f2py/f2py2e.py) into 2 files. One file `f2pyarg.py` is responsible for parsing arguments file while other `service.py` deals with `f2py` core functionalities.

Some upcoming goals are:

- [x] Implement [run_main()](https://github.com/numpy/numpy/blob/0f7eaf8971541e9f7e99c91b3a21e007f9d64c0c/numpy/f2py/f2py2e.py#L411). It is the function responsible for generating wrappers and `.pyf` files.
- [x] Implement [run_compile()](https://github.com/numpy/numpy/blob/0f7eaf8971541e9f7e99c91b3a21e007f9d64c0c/numpy/f2py/f2py2e.py#L505) responsible for compiling and building shared libraries.
- [ ] Decide and implement deprecation of flags. For ex. - `--f2py-wrapper-output`, `--skip-empty-wrappers`
- [ ] Code cleanup. Will involve refactoring and deciding which flags belong to which subparser.

Its the first time I am using it.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 25, 4, 50, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'NamamiShanker', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 928787781, 'comment_body': '> can you please share some relevant docs where I can read more about builtin types and the __future__ module? Its the first time I am using it.

So the `__future__` module is somewhat unique in that imports therefrom enable behavior that will only become default in future python versions. Older examples of this include the `print` functions and `with` statement, but a more recent addition is the postponed evaluation of annotations ([PEP 563](https://peps.python.org/pep-0563/#abstract)), which implicitly stringifies all annotations during runtime (_e.g._ `a: int` automatically becomes `a: "int"`).

> Can `Any`, `Optional` be replaced by some `builtins` types?

For `Any` you'll still have to rely on `typing`, as it lacks an equivalent in `builtins`. On the other hand, `Optional[~T]` is merely an alias for `~T | None`, so you can just use the pipe operator there as you'd use for any other union.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 25, 11, 42, 59, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'BvB93', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 931076266, 'comment_body': "Thanks for mentioning this, didn't know about the `__future` module. I have made the changes. pr_title: ENH: Meson build system support for F2PY's `f2py -c` command
pr_body:
<!--         ----------------------------------------------------------------
                MAKE SURE YOUR PR GETS THE ATTENTION IT DESERVES!
                ----------------------------------------------------------------

*  FORMAT IT RIGHT:
      https://www.numpy.org/devdocs/dev/development_workflow.html#writing-the-commit-message

*  IF IT'S A NEW FEATURE OR API CHANGE, TEST THE WATERS:
      https://www.numpy.org/devdocs/dev/development_workflow.html#get-the-mailing-list-s-opinion

*  HIT ALL THE GUIDELINES:
      https://numpy.org/devdocs/dev/index.html#guidelines

*  WHAT TO DO IF WE HAVEN'T GOTTEN BACK TO YOU:
      https://www.numpy.org/devdocs/dev/development_workflow.html#getting-your-pr-reviewed
-->

This PR is a continuation of my older PR for [implementing F2PY's fronted with `argparse`](https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/21923).

[My blog](https://namamishanker.github.io/posts/f2py_meson_backend/) explains the core ideas behind the changes.

This PR introduces a new flag for F2PY - `--backend` which can accept build system for building Python extension modules.

An example to produce a Python module out of the classic [fibonacci sequence Fortran program](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/f2py/f2py.getting-started.html#the-quick-and-smart-way) will be:-

```
f2py -m fib --lower -c --backend=meson fibfortran.f
```
The output thus produced works correctly:
```
>>> import fib
>>> print(fib.fib.__doc__)
a = fib(n)

Wrapper for ``fib``.

Parameters
----------
n : input int

Returns
-------
a : rank-1 array('d') with bounds (n)

>>> print(fib.fib(8))
[ 0.  1.  1.  2.  3.  5.  8. 13.]
>>> 
```

The default value of `--backend` flag is `distutils` making this feature completely backwards compatible.
